rding to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Sybilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sibilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sybille","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Sybil</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Sibella Powtrell was born in 1230. She married Sir. Henry Powtrell in 1245, in Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1230–":"1230–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1245–1276":"1245–1276","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1245":"1245","1276":"1276","1230":"1230","Thrumpton Hall, Nottingham, Nottingham, England":"Thrumpton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1230–":"1230–Kuollut","1230–Male":"1